1362@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Protected Areas in Norway@1@4@@danf@24-8-2004
1363@unknown@formal@none@1@S@General Protection@1@2@@danf@24-8-2004
1364@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Norway has a very special nature, and many laws are given to protect it from being destroyed.@1@17@@danf@24-8-2004
1365@unknown@formal@none@1@@Firstly, the Every Mans Right gives everyone the right to be in the nature, as long as nothing is done to harm the nature.@0@24@@danf@24-8-2004
1366@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It is illegal to put up fences outside cultivated areas, and it's illegal to put up signs denying anyone access.@1@20@@danf@24-8-2004
1367@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It's also illegal to put up advertisement boards outside cities.@1@10@@danf@24-8-2004
1368@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Travel with motorized vehicles outside roads is illegal without special reason and permission.@1@13@@danf@24-8-2004
1369@unknown@formal@none@1@@Such travel with snowmobile is legal on Svalbard and in Finnmark on marked routes.@0@14@@danf@24-8-2004
1370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It's also generally illegal to build huts, houses, roads or bridges outside cultivated areas without permission from the local municipality.@1@20@@danf@24-8-2004
1371@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In addition to these general rules there are several kinds of special protected areas, where the rules are stronger.@1@19@@danf@24-8-2004
1372@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These are:@1@2@@danf@24-8-2004
1373@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Landscape Protected Area (Landskapsvernområde)@1@4@@danf@24-8-2004
1374@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In these areas permissons will not be given for anything that will change the character of the landscape.@1@18@@danf@24-8-2004
1375@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This is the mildest form of protection, and is normally given to medium-sized areas without roads or any other motorized means of transportation, but with some technical installations.@1@28@@danf@24-8-2004
1376@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Wild mountain areas with some regulated lakes often get this status.@1@11@@danf@24-8-2004
1377@unknown@formal@none@1@S@National Park (Nasjonalpark)@1@3@@danf@24-8-2004
1378@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A National Park is a larger area without any technical installations.@1@11@@danf@24-8-2004
1379@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A national park is according to the definition "an area where the nature is nationally and globally special, and therefore worth protection".@1@22@@danf@24-8-2004
1380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@As this is written there are 16 National Parks in Norway, but the number is still rising.@1@17@@danf@24-8-2004
1381@unknown@formal@none@1@S@National Parks do not have roads, and motorized travel is usually only allowed for critical missions.@1@16@@danf@24-8-2004
1382@unknown@formal@none@1@@Most of Norways National Parks today are mountain areas, and many of the most known mountain areas have this status.@0@20@@danf@24-8-2004
1383@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Nature Reserve (Naturreservat)@1@3@@danf@24-8-2004
1384@unknown@formal@none@1@@The status of Nature Reserve is usually given to a small area with very special type of landscape, or - more common - wildlife.@0@24@@danf@24-8-2004
1385@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Nature Reserve is the strongest protection.@1@6@@danf@24-8-2004
1386@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Motorized travel is absolutely not allowed, and in some cases travel is not allowed at all.@1@16@@danf@24-8-2004
1387@unknown@formal@none@1@S@(Although this is rare, due to the Every Mans Right.@1@10@@danf@24-8-2004
1388@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It is usually only practised at bird colonies at the coast.)@1@11@@danf@24-8-2004
1389@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are many small Nature Reserves in Norway.@1@8@@danf@24-8-2004
1390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Mountain Lodges@1@2@@danf@24-8-2004
1391@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Different types of Lodges@1@4@@danf@24-8-2004
1392@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In most areas in Norwegian Mountains you will find different types of Mountain Lodges.@1@14@@danf@24-8-2004
1393@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Many lodges are owned and operated by member organizations of The Norwegian Mountain Touring Assosiation.@1@15@@danf@24-8-2004
1394@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These lodges meet a certain standard, and have standardized prices with discounts for members.@1@14@@danf@24-8-2004
1395@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are also private lodges, many of which also have discounts for DNT (Norwegian Mountain Touring Assosiation) members.@1@18@@danf@24-8-2004
1396@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are staffed lodges, selv-service lodges and non-service lodges.@1@9@@danf@24-8-2004
1397@unknown@formal@none@1@S@At the staffed lodges you can buy meals (breakfast and dinner) and many lodges offer snacks, beer and wine.@1@19@@danf@24-8-2004
1398@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Staffed mountain lodges are marked on the maps as red squares.@1@11@@danf@24-8-2004
1399@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Self-service lodges are unstaffed lodges equipped with stoves, firewood and a stock of food.@1@14@@danf@24-8-2004
1400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@You just take what you want and pay at the lodge with cash or your credit card.@1@17@@danf@24-8-2004
1401@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This system is based on trust and is unique.@1@9@@danf@24-8-2004
1402@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It might seem strange, but experience shows that people in the mountain are honest.@1@14@@danf@24-8-2004
1403@unknown@formal@none@1@@Self-service are shown on the maps as a half-by-half red/white squares.@0@11@@danf@24-8-2004
1404@unknown@formal@none@1@S@No-service lodges work the same way as self-service lodges, except there is no food here, so you have to bring your own.@1@22@@danf@24-8-2004
1405@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Anyway no-service lodges always have heating ovens and some kind of cooking equipment.@1@13@@danf@24-8-2004
